[stdout] {"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772767699725,"sessionID":"ses_33ecfbdcaffeIJmvksryAM5lBI","part":{"id":"prt_cc1306292001duuBfvhRoGe1cB","sessionID":"ses_33ecfbdcaffeIJmvksryAM5lBI","messageID":"msg_cc1305b540017ETWqxRzGFQhfm","type":"tool","callID":"call_NERyqg82yUBPPp2fz89iSVdx","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/SYNTAX.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/SYNTAX.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # tscircuit syntax primer\n2: \n3: ## 1) Root element\n4: \n5: A circuit is typically a default export that returns a `<board />` or a form-factor board component from `@tscircuit/common`.\n6: \n7: Example:\n8: \n9: ```tsx\n10: import React from \"react\"\n11: \n12: export default () => (\n13:   <board width=\"10mm\" height=\"10mm\">\n14:     <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" />\n15:   </board>\n16: )\n17: ```\n18: \n19: ## 2) Layout properties\n20: \n21: You can place nearly any element with:\n22: - `pcbX`, `pcbY` (PCB position)\n23: - `pcbRotation`\n24: - `layer` (e.g., `\"bottom\"`)\n25: \n26: For schematics:\n27: - `schX`, `schY`\n28: - `schRotation`\n29: - `schOrientation`\n30: \n31: Units\n32: - Numbers are interpreted as mm.\n33: - Strings can include units (e.g., `\"0.1in\"`, `\"2.54mm\"`).\n34: \n35: ## 3) Pin labels with `pinLabels`\n36: \n37: Use `pinLabels` to map physical pin numbers to meaningful names. This is essential for chips and ICs.\n38: \n39: ```tsx\n40: <chip\n41:   name=\"U1\"\n42:   footprint=\"qfp32\"\n43:   pinLabels={{\n44:     pin1: [\"GP0\", \"SPI0_RX\", \"I2C0_SDA\", \"UART0_TX\"],\n45:     pin2: [\"GP1\", \"SPI0_CS\", \"I2C0_SCL\", \"UART0_RX\"],\n46:     pin3: \"GND\",\n47:     // ...\n48:   }}\n49: />\n50: ```\n51: \n52: With multi-alias, any of the names can be used in traces:\n53: \n54: ```tsx\n55: <trace from=\"U1.GP0\" to=\"U2.SDA\" />\n56: <trace from=\"U1.SPI0_RX\" to=\"U3.MISO\" />\n57: ```\n58: \n59: ## 4) Pin attributes with `pinAttributes`\n60: \n61: Use `pinAttributes` to add semantic metadata to pins. This enables DRC checks, schematic arrows, and board-level pinout exposure.\n62: \n63: Example using a 555 timer (NE555):\n64: \n65: ```tsx\n66: <chip\n67:   name=\"U1\"\n68:   footprint=\"dip8\"\n69:   pinLabels={{\n70:     pin1: \"GND\",\n71:     pin2: \"TRIG\",\n72:     pin3: \"OUT\",\n73:     pin4: \"RESET\",\n74:     pin5: \"CTRL\",\n75:     pin6: \"THRES\",\n76:     pin7: \"DISCH\",\n77:     pin8: \"VCC\",\n78:   }}\n79:   pinAttributes={{\n80:     VCC: { requiresPower: true },\n81:     RESET: { mustBeConnected: true },\n82:   }}\n83: />\n84: ```\n85: \n86: Available attributes:\n87: \n88: | Attribute | Type | Description |\n89: |-----------|------|-------------|\n90: | `requiresPower` | boolean | Signal goes INTO the chip (shows input arrow on schematic) |\n91: | `providesPower` | boolean | Signal comes OUT of the chip (shows output arrow on schematic) |\n92: | `mustBeConnected` | boolean | DRC error if this pin is left floating |\n93: | `includeInBoardPinout` | boolean | Expose this pin to the board-level pinout |\n94: \n95: ## 5) Type-safe chip components\n96: \n97: For reusable chip components, define `pinLabels` as a const and use `ChipProps` for type safety:\n98: \n99: ```tsx\n100: import type { ChipProps } from \"tscircuit\"\n101: \n102: const pinLabels = {\n103:   pin1: \"VCC\",\n104:   pin2: \"GND\",\n105:   pin3: [\"SDA\", \"I2C_DATA\"],\n106:   pin4: [\"SCL\", \"I2C_CLK\"],\n107: } as const\n108: \n109: export const MyChip = (props: ChipProps<typeof pinLabels>) => (\n110:   <chip\n111:     {...props}\n112:     pinLabels={pinLabels}\n113:     footprint=\"soic4\"\n114:   />\n115: )\n116: ```\n117: \n118: ## 6) Connectivity with `<trace />`\n119: \n120: Connect pins with port selectors:\n121: \n122: ```tsx\n123: <trace from=\"R1.pin1\" to=\"C1.pin1\" />\n124: ```\n125: \n126: Connect to named nets. Net names must start with a letter or underscore and can only contain letters, numbers and underscores. \n127: \n128: ```tsx\n129: <trace from=\"U1.pin1\" to=\"net.GND\" />\n130: <trace from=\"U1.pin8\" to=\"net.VCC\" />\n131: <trace from=\"U1.pin8\" to=\"net.V3_3\" />\n132: ```\n133: \n134: Pin labels (in `pinLabels`) can contain letters, numbers, and underscores. Unlike net names, pin labels **can** start with a number (e.g., `\"3V3\"` is valid).\n135: \n136: Useful trace props (optional)\n137: - `width` / `thickness`\n138: - `minLength` / `maxLength`\n139: \n140: ## 7) Grouping for PCB layout\n141: \n142: Use `<group />` like a container to move/layout parts together.\n143: \n144: ```tsx\n145: <board width=\"20mm\" height=\"20mm\">\n146:   <group pcbX={5} pcbY={5}>\n147:     <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" pcbX={2.5} pcbY={2.5} />\n148:     <resistor name=\"R2\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" pcbX={2.5} pcbY={0} />\n149:     <resistor name=\"R3\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" pcbX={2.5} pcbY={-2.5} />\n150:   </group>\n151: </board>\n152: ```\n153: \n154: ## 8) Schematic pin arrangement\n155: \n156: Control how pins appear on the schematic symbol with `schPinArrangement`:\n157: \n158: ```tsx\n159: <chip\n160:   name=\"U1\"\n161:   footprint=\"soic16\"\n162:   pinLabels={{\n163:     pin1: \"VCC1\",\n164:     pin2: \"IN1\",\n165:     pin3: \"IN2\",\n166:     pin4: \"IN3\",\n167:     pin5: \"IN4\",\n168:     pin6: \"GND1\",\n169:     pin7: \"GND2\",\n170:     pin8: \"VCC2\",\n171:     pin9: \"OUT1\",\n172:     pin10: \"OUT2\",\n173:     pin11: \"OUT3\",\n174:     pin12: \"OUT4\",\n175:   }}\n176:   schPinArrangement={{\n177:     topSide: { pins: [\"VCC1\", \"VCC2\"], direction: \"left-to-right\" },\n178:     bottomSide: { pins: [\"GND1\", \"GND2\"], direction: \"left-to-right\" },\n179:     leftSide: { pins: [\"IN1\", \"IN2\", \"IN3\", \"IN4\"], direction: \"top-to-bottom\" },\n180:     rightSide: { pins: [\"OUT1\", \"OUT2\", \"OUT3\", \"OUT4\"], direction: \"top-to-bottom\" },\n181:   }}\n182: />\n183: ```\n184: \n185: Available sides: `leftSide`, `rightSide`, `topSide`, `bottomSide`\n186: - Left/right sides use `direction: \"top-to-bottom\"` or `\"bottom-to-top\"`\n187: - Top/bottom sides use `direction: \"left-to-right\"` or `\"right-to-left\"`\n188: \n189: ## 9) Manufacturing helpers\n190: \n191: For turnkey assembly you will often want:\n192: - `supplierPartNumbers` (pin a specific supplier SKU/part number)\n193: - `doNotPlace` (exclude from automated placement)\n194: \n195: Example:\n196: \n197: ```tsx\n198: <capacitor\n199:   name=\"C1\"\n200:   capacitance=\"100nF\"\n201:   footprint=\"0402\"\n202:   supplierPartNumbers={{ jlcpcb: \"C14663\" }}\n203: />\n204: \n205: <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"10k\" footprint=\"0402\" doNotPlace />\n206: ```\n\n(End of file - total 206 lines)\n</content>","title":"workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/SYNTAX.md","metadata":{"preview":"# tscircuit syntax primer\n\n## 1) Root element\n\nA circuit is typically a default export that returns a `<board />` or a form-factor board component from `@tscircuit/common`.\n\nExample:\n\n```tsx\nimport React from \"react\"\n\nexport default () => (\n  <board width=\"10mm\" height=\"10mm\">\n    <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" />\n  </board>\n)\n```\n\n## 2) Layout properties\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772767699604,"end":1772767699714}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}}}}

